{"id":"4W3i2hyrJTVfcLq85rWgduVQ3y3BMzrSD4pVUCMqPpFhmXWpqxQ","title":"Hacker News: Front Page","displayTitle":"HN Front","url":"https://hnrss.org/frontpage?points=75","feedLink":"https://news.ycombinator.com/","items":[{"title":"Flappy Bird in 1000 lines of C","url":"https://github.com/alxyng/flappybird","date":1733333757,"author":"alexyoung91","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://github.com/alxyng/flappybird\">https://github.com/alxyng/flappybird</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42319798\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42319798</a></p>\n<p>Points: 121</p>\n<p># Comments: 41</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Ask HN: What are the best programmable holiday lights?","url":"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42341809","date":1733505626,"author":"sh1mmer","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>I am replacing some old outdoor lights and I want to get LED lights that I can program? Any suggestions on the best ones? Ideally replaceable/extendable light strings with some kind of programmable controller that has usb/wifi. If it has an app my family can use that’s a plus.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42341809\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42341809</a></p>\n<p>Points: 110</p>\n<p># Comments: 55</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Mise: Dev tools, env vars, task runner","url":"https://github.com/jdx/mise","date":1733556100,"author":"ksec","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://github.com/jdx/mise\">https://github.com/jdx/mise</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42347917\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42347917</a></p>\n<p>Points: 185</p>\n<p># Comments: 106</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Insects rely on sounds made by distressed vegetation to guide reproduction","url":"https://www.nytimes.com/2024/12/06/science/moths-hearing-plant-sounds.html","date":1733607733,"author":"tintinnabula","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2024/12/06/science/moths-hearing-plant-sounds.html\">https://www.nytimes.com/2024/12/06/science/moths-hearing-plant-sounds.html</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42353066\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42353066</a></p>\n<p>Points: 156</p>\n<p># Comments: 129</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"\"BGP at home\": getting a DIA circuit installed at home","url":"https://aaka.sh/posts/20230129-bgp-at-home.html","date":1733615111,"author":"tripdout","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://aaka.sh/posts/20230129-bgp-at-home.html\">https://aaka.sh/posts/20230129-bgp-at-home.html</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42353778\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42353778</a></p>\n<p>Points: 200</p>\n<p># Comments: 51</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Show HN: Cut the crap – remove AI bullshit from websites","url":"https://cut-the-crab.streamlit.app/","date":1733655579,"author":"muc-martin","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>I’ve spent a lot of time reading articles that promise a lot but never give me what I’m looking for. They’re full of clickbait titles, scary claims, and pointless filler. It’s frustrating, and it’s a waste of my time.<p>So I made a tool. You give it a URL, and it tries to cut through all that noise. It gives you a shorter version of the content without all the nonsense. I built this because I’m tired of falling for the same tricks. I just want the facts, not a bunch of filler.<p>What do you think? I’m also thinking of making a Chrome extension that does something similar—like a reader mode, but one that actually removes the crap that gets in the way of real information. Feedback welcome.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42356443\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42356443</a></p>\n<p>Points: 165</p>\n<p># Comments: 98</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Qutebrowser: A keyboard-driven, Vim-like browser","url":"https://github.com/qutebrowser/qutebrowser","date":1733659574,"author":"AbuAssar","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://github.com/qutebrowser/qutebrowser\">https://github.com/qutebrowser/qutebrowser</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42356668\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42356668</a></p>\n<p>Points: 89</p>\n<p># Comments: 43</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"Mend it Mark gets suspect copyright strike for £25k audio amp repair","url":"https://hackaday.com/2024/12/07/the-25000-tom-evans-pre-amp-repair-and-a-copyright-strike/","date":1733665674,"author":"Workaccount2","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://hackaday.com/2024/12/07/the-25000-tom-evans-pre-amp-repair-and-a-copyright-strike/\">https://hackaday.com/2024/12/07/the-25000-tom-evans-pre-amp-repair-and-a-copyright-strike/</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a href=\"https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42357115\">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=42357115</a></p>\n<p>Points: 210</p>\n<p># Comments: 78</p>\n","flags":null,"enclosureUrl":"","enclosureMime":""},{"title":"How much do I need to change my face to avoid facial recognition?","url":"https://gizmodo.com/how-much-do-i-need-to-change-my-face-to-avoid-facial-recognition-2000533755","date":1733668701,"author":"pseudolus","unread":true,"desc":"","content":"\n<p>Article URL: <a href=\"https://gizmodo.com/how-much-do-i-need-to-change-my-face-to-avoid-facial-recognition-2000533755\">https://gizmodo.com/how-much-do-i-need-to-change-my-face-to-avoid-facial-recognition-2000533755</a></p>\n<p>Comments URL: <a hr